Phase 0: restore a green baseline before adding more feature work. Repair the style-block parser in index.ts:304 so the existing suite in index.test.ts:4 passes again, and keep that suite blocking in ci.yaml:30. Also make the repo instructions truthful about platform-specific local behavior by aligning README.md:64 and next.config.ts:4 with the current Linux-first CI assumptions. Exit when CI is green and local setup guidance no longer implies Windows behaviors that are not actually supported.

Phase 1: harden verification for identity, tenancy, and lifecycle instead of redesigning them. Keep the current OIDC, tenancy, and RBAC shape in auth.go:67, rbac.go:15, and router.go:74, but add integration tests for workspace role enforcement, tenant isolation, published-only runtime access in apps.go:230, and admin-only publish and approval actions. Exit when there is a repeatable RBAC matrix and tenant-isolation suite, not just route-level code.

Phase 2: fix builder correctness and persist manual edits as first-class data. Add node metadata storage to both apps and app versions, preferably as a JSONB column keyed by node id and carrying at least manuallyEdited, then thread it through 002_create_apps_versions.up.sql:14, apps.go:66, api.ts:144, and apps/web/app/builder/[appId]/hooks/useAutosave.ts. Mark all builder-originated edits as manual, not just inspector property changes in apps/web/app/builder/[appId]/Inspector.tsx: include move and resize in apps/web/app/builder/[appId]/CanvasEditor.tsx, plus add, delete, and layout changes in apps/web/app/builder/[appId]/page.tsx. Then remove the fixed 24-column cap in apps/web/app/builder/[appId]/CanvasEditor.tsx and apps/web/app/app/[appId]/RuntimeRenderer.tsx by switching to unbounded coordinates and extent-based rendering. Exit when manual edits survive save, reload, publish, and rollback, and the canvas no longer has a hard horizontal limit.

Phase 3: replace full-document AI overwrites with protected change application. The current assistant path blindly replaces the document in apps/web/app/builder/[appId]/page.tsx and persists it with a full update in generation.go:324, even though the protection logic already exists in index.ts:199. Change the worker to produce a candidate revision, validate and repair it before persistence, compute a diff against the current document, and apply only allowed changes unless the user explicitly requests overwrite. Exit when chat revisions preserve protected nodes by default and invalid AI DSL never reaches storage.

Phase 4: bring connector behavior to one consistent capability matrix. Extract the live relational query runners now embedded in workflow.go:303 into shared execution helpers and use them from connectors.go:360 so dashboard queries and workflow queries support the same relational set. Expand live connection testing in connectors.go:179 to cover MySQL, SQL Server, GraphQL, and CSV behavior, add missing REST schema discovery in schema.go:90, and either expose CSV import through the API and builder UI or explicitly move it out of scope. Exit when the supported connector list is identical across create, test, schema discovery, query, import, and workflow execution.

Phase 5: add a true draft preview path and finish lifecycle correctness. The builder currently only exposes preview once the app is already published in apps/web/app/builder/[appId]/page.tsx, and the runtime route only reads published versions in apps/web/app/app/[appId]/page.tsx. Add a builder-only draft preview endpoint and route that renders the current draft safely, keep the published route backed by immutable versions, and snapshot both DSL and node metadata during publish and rollback. Exit when admins and builders can validate drafts before publication and end users still cannot access unpublished work.

Phase 6: normalize workflow mutation safety and dashboard behavior. The mutation path in workflow.go:234 currently records a completed result even when nothing actually executes, as shown in workflow.go:255. Change the rule so every mutation step either creates an approval gate, executes only after approval with a verifiable approval id, or fails closed; never mark a mutation successful unless it actually ran. Exit when workflow history reflects real execution outcomes and all mutating external actions are approval-gated end to end.

Phase 7: prove self-hosted and release-readiness claims with drills, not docs alone. Keep the existing upgrade, backup, restore, HA, and observability assets in UPGRADING.md, README.md, and the deployment manifests, but add automated fresh-install smoke tests, upgrade preservation tests, backup and restore drills, audit export checks, secret-rotation rehearsal, and tenant-leakage validation. Exit when Compose and Helm installs, upgrades, restores, and published-app continuity are exercised automatically rather than assumed from documentation.